{{Infobox book | name = Dear Socks, Dear Buddy: Kids' Letters to the First Pets | title_orig = | translator = | image = File:DearSocksDearBuddy.JPG | caption = | author = [[Hillary Rodham Clinton]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = | language = English | series = | subject = | genre = | publisher = [[Simon & Schuster]] | release_date = November 17, 1998 | english_release_date = | media_type = Print ([[Hardcover]]) | pages = 208 | isbn = 0-684-85778-2 | dewey= | congress= | oclc= | preceded_by = [[It Takes a Village|It Takes a Village: And Other Lessons Children Teach Us]] ''(1996)' | followed_by = [[An Invitation to the White House|An Invitation to the White House: At Home with History]] ''(2000)' }}
'''''Dear Socks, Dear Buddy: Kids' Letters to the First Pets''''' is a 1998 [[children's book]] written by [[First Lady of the United States]] [[Hillary Rodham Clinton]]. It concerns the two pets that lived in the [[White House]] during the [[Clinton administration]], [[Socks (cat)|Socks the cat]] and [[Buddy (dog)|Buddy the dog]].
==Description== The book includes more than 50 letters written to the First Pets by children and more than 80 photographs of Socks and Buddy. Examples of questions that letters asked include, "Who do you like best? Mr. Clinton? Mrs. Clinton or Chelsea?" and, "How do you like being a dog, Buddy? I like being a person."<ref name="nyt-announce"/><ref name="cst-about"/> Socks was also asked if he was allowed to watch [[MTV]]<ref name="cst-about"/> and Buddy was asked if he ever got petted by the [[Spice Girls]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.google.com/search?q=%22dear+socks%22+%22dear+buddy%22+%22spice+girls%22&source=lnms&tbm=bks&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjjhqq6zsPaAhVik-AKHTBQDZA4ChD8BQgQKAE&biw=1044&bih=757&dpr=1.2 | title='Dear Buddy, Did You Ever Get Petted By the Spice Girls?' | magazine=[[Newsweek]] | date=October 1998 | page=108}}</ref>
The book also includes several sections of text by Clinton discussing the two pets' habits, as well as the rivalry between them. Clinton also provided a history of the previous pets that had lived in the White House.<ref name="cst-about"/> The text also dispensed some advice on caring for pets and told parents to encourage children to express themselves through writing.<ref name="cst-about">{{cite news | url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4473145.html | title=Socking it to Buddy; First lady's pet book is a tail-all account | newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] | date=December 6, 1998 | first=Paul D. | last=Colford |subscription= yes |via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}</ref>
The last chapter of the book is titled "A Note on Saving America's Parks and Treasures".<ref>''Dear Socks, Dear Buddy'', pp. 193–202.</ref>
==History== [[File:Hillary Clinton in 1999 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|upright|The First Lady with Socks and Buddy in 1999]]
The idea for the book originated with her publisher, [[Simon & Schuster]], who were interested in a follow-up to Clinton's best-selling 1996 volume ''[[It Takes a Village]]''.<ref name="nyt-announce">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/06/08/business/media-talk-the-first-pets-get-their-own-book.html | title=Media Talk: The First Pets Get Their Own Book | first=Doreen | last=Carvajal | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | date=June 8, 1998}}</ref> It also followed in the pawsteps of prior First Lady [[Barbara Bush]]'s popular 1990 effort ''[[Millie's Book]]'', about [[Millie (dog)|the prior White House dog]].<ref name="sr-announce"/> Plans for ''Dear Socks, Dear Buddy'' were announced in June 1998<ref name="sr-announce">{{cite news | url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1314&dat=19980605&id=Z4BXAAAAIBAJ&sjid=uvEDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4264,2334094&hl=en | title=First Lady's book deal is animal act | agency=[[Associated Press]] | newspaper=[[The Spokesman-Review]] | location=Spokane, Washington | date=June 5, 1998 | page=A4}}</ref> and it was stated that [[Linda Kulman]], a reporter based in Washington, would assist Clinton in the writing.<ref name="sr-announce"/> [[Book Magazine|''Book'']] magazine would subsequently characterize Kulman's role as that of a [[ghostwriter]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-82260536.html | title= Master Class: Want to Write a Book? Columbia Prof Sam Freedman Can Show You the Way. | magazine=[[Book Magazine|''Book'']] | date=January 2002 | last=Temple-Raston | first=Dina |subscription= yes |via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}</ref>
The book had a first printing put at somewhere between 400,000 and 500,000&nbsp;copies.<ref name="cst-about"/><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-675896.html | title=No Thanks For the Memoirs; Publishers Turn Down Lewinsky Book, But Other Political Page-Turners Do Well | newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] | date=September 17, 1998 | first=David | last=Streitfeld |subscription= yes |via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}</ref> Its actual sales were around 350,000&nbsp;copies.<ref name="wapo-prep">{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/2000/10/04/white-house-welcome/2be3bfdd-e26b-420b-a7f0-f9df48cc373b/ | title=White House Welcome | first=Roxanne | last=Roberts | newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] | date=October 4, 2000}}</ref> <!-- Can't find it on NYT best-seller list - see https://www.nytimes.com/books/98/11/29/bsp/besthardnonfiction.html and weeks forward - maybe because a children's book and not included in any of their lists at the time? --> The book did not sell as well as ''It Takes a Village'' had, in part because the nature of the book was different and in part because Clinton did not engage in the same level of promotional activity for it.<ref name="wapo-prep"/><ref name="colford-books"/> The book came out as the [[Lewinsky scandal]] turned into the [[impeachment of Bill Clinton]], which contributed to Clinton's lessened efforts in promoting the book.<ref name="colford-books">{{cite news | url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-23099637.html | title=With the Trial Over, the Storytelling Begins | first=Paul D. | last=Colford | newspaper=[[The Buffalo News]] | date=February 23, 1999 |via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}</ref> {{clear}}
==Proceeds== Clinton received no advance for writing the book.<ref name="tsj-announ">{{cite news | url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/1098961/?terms=%22dear+socks,+dear+buddy%22 | title=Book based on letters to Clintons' pets | agency=[[Associated Press]] | newspaper=[[The Salina Journal]] | date=June 4, 1998 | page=A4 | via=[[Newspapers.com]] |subscription= yes }}</ref> All of her proceeds from book sales and related publishing rights were donated to the [[National Park Foundation]], the official charity of America's [[National Park Service]].<ref name="cst-about"/> The publisher said it would donate some of its proceeds to the foundation as well.<ref name="tsj-announ"/>
The foundation was given possession of the copyright to the book, which simplified the tax aspects related to awarding profits to the foundation, thus eliminating some complexities that Clinton had encountered in donating the proceeds of ''It Takes a Village''.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/04/15/us/the-clintons-pay-92104-in-federal-income-taxes.html | title=The Clintons Pay $92,104 In Federal Income Taxes | first=David Cay | last=Johnston | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | date= April 15, 2000}}</ref>
