{{Infobox film | name = The Cure for Insomnia | director = John Henry Timmis IV | producer = Joseph Emm Matune | writer = Nickoli Schirripa | starring = Lee Groban | cinematography = John Henry Timmis IV | editing = Sean Jay Manning | released = January 31, 1987 | runtime = 5220 minutes (87 hours) | country = USA | awards = ''[[Guinness World Records|Guinness World Record]]'': World's longest film | language = English }} '''''The Cure for Insomnia''''', directed by John Henry Timmis IV, is a 1987 [[experimental film]] which was, according to ''[[Guinness World Records]]'', the [[List of longest films by running time|longest running]] film at the time. This record has since been surpassed by several other films.<ref>"The Longest Movies Ever Made," ''[[Orange Coast Magazine]]'', May 1989, p. 176.</ref> At 5,220 minutes long (87 hours, or 3 days and 15 hours) in length, the film has no plot, instead consisting of artist L. D. Groban reading his 4,080-page poem ''A Cure for Insomnia''<ref>Bruce Felton, ''What Were They Thinking?: Really Bad Ideas Throughout History'', The Lyons Press, 2003, p. 96.</ref> over the course of three and a half days, spliced with occasional clips from [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] and [[pornographic]] videos.<ref>Nick Belardes, ''A People's History of the Peculiar: A Freak Show of Facts, Random Obsessions and Astounding Truths'', Viva Editions, 2014, p. 154.</ref>
It was first played in its entirety at [[Art Institute of Chicago|The School of the Art Institute]] in [[Chicago, Illinois]], from January 31 to February 3, 1987, in one continuous showing. It has not been released on DVD or other home video formats and all known copies are considered as lost. {{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}
